ergo animus qu: many editors (Or. Hei. etc.) omit qui, but there seems to be no satisfactory theory to account for its presence except the view of sn. (adopted by Schiche) who holds that qui arose out of quidem, the animus quidem or ipse animus being finished with here and the question of its sedes and forma being taken up in §⁶7- The choice seems to lie between this and the view of Kuh. who retains qui, observing ‘Ipsi Ciceroni uitium orationis tribuendum puto; uidetur enim primum orationem sic conformatorus fuisse: ergo animus, qui, ut ego dico, diuinus est, ut Euripides dicere audet, deus, si deus aut anima aut ignis est, idern est (he. aut anima aut ignis est); deindeautem inchoatam structuram mu· tauit, ryuo maiore ui animum hominis efferret.
